/*
directives:

#include - include files
This directive inserts the contents of another file (for example, a library) into the current file before compilation starts.

#define - define macros
This creates a macro, which is a name that gets replaced with a piece of text or value before compilation.

#undef - undefined a macro 
Removes a previously defined macro

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

A.conditional compilation -
These allow you to compile certain parts of your code only if certain conditions are met.
#if 
#ifdef
#ifndef
#else
#elif
#elifdef
#elifndef 
#endif

example with ifdef:
#define DEBUG

#ifdef DEBUG
    std::cout << "Debug mode on" << std::endl;
#endif

The code inside will only compile if DEBUG is defined.
{
Example with #if and #else:
#define VERSION 2

#if VERSION == 1
    std::cout << "Old version" << std::endl;
#else
    std::cout << "New version" << std::endl;
#endif
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#pragma -
These are special commands that depend on the compiler.

Examples:
#pragma once


